<div class="wrap">

  <div class="skillbox">
    <span class="tag-label skill">Master This First — Energy Flows One Way; Matter Cycles</span>
    <p>This single distinction organizes the entire unit. Energy enters an ecosystem from the sun, gets used, and is ultimately lost as heat — it flows through the system once and is gone, which is exactly why every ecosystem needs a constant new input of sunlight to keep functioning. Matter — carbon, nitrogen, phosphorus, water — is different: there's a fixed amount of it on Earth, so instead of flowing through and disappearing, it CYCLES, passing repeatedly between living organisms, the atmosphere, water, and rock. Every time this unit discusses energy, expect a one-way flow with real losses at every step. Every time it discusses a nutrient, expect a cycle with no true "loss," just movement between reservoirs.</p>
  </div>

  <h2 id="s11"><span class="num">1.1</span>Ecosystem Structure and Ecosystem Services</h2>
  <p>An ecosystem is a community of organisms interacting with each other and with their physical, nonliving environment. Before getting into specific biomes or cycles, it's worth being precise about the vocabulary this unit — and the entire course — is built on.</p>

  <table class="formula-table">
    <thead><tr><th>Term</th><th>Definition</th></tr></thead>
    <tbody>
      <tr><td>Population</td><td>All the individuals of one species living in a given area</td></tr>
      <tr><td>Community</td><td>All the populations of different species living and interacting in a given area</td></tr>
      <tr><td>Ecosystem</td><td>A community plus its nonliving (abiotic) environment — soil, water, air, sunlight</td></tr>
      <tr><td>Biome</td><td>A large geographic region characterized by a distinct climate and dominant plant/animal life</td></tr>
      <tr><td>Biosphere</td><td>The sum of all of Earth's ecosystems — every region where life exists</td></tr>
    </tbody>
  </table>

  <div class="key-idea">
    <span class="tag-label idea">Key Idea — Ecosystem Services Are Benefits Humans Get for Free</span>
    <p>Ecosystem services are the benefits humans derive from healthy, functioning ecosystems, without paying for them directly — things like pollination of crops by insects, water filtration by wetlands, flood control by forests and floodplains, carbon storage by forests and oceans, and soil formation. This concept matters enormously later in the course, since a huge share of environmental policy is really an argument about how to value and protect services that don't show up on a normal balance sheet, but whose loss (a collapsed pollinator population, a destroyed wetland) can be extraordinarily costly to replace artificially.</p>
  </div>

  <div class="trap">
    <span class="tag-label trap">Watch Out For This</span>
    <p>Don't confuse a population, a community, and an ecosystem — this exact vocabulary distinction is tested constantly and is easy to blur under time pressure. A population is ONE species. A community is MULTIPLE species interacting. An ecosystem is that community PLUS its nonliving environment. If a question describes only living organisms with no mention of soil, water, or climate, it's likely asking about a community, not a full ecosystem.</p>
  </div>

  <div class="worked">
    <span class="tag-label example">Worked Example 1</span>
    <p><strong>Identifying an Ecosystem Service.</strong> A coastal wetland reduces the severity of storm surge flooding for a nearby town during a hurricane, at no direct cost to the town. Identify the ecosystem service being provided and explain why this matters for environmental policy.</p>
    <details class="solution"><summary>Show the reasoning</summary>
      <div class="sol-content">This is a <strong>flood control / storm buffering ecosystem service</strong>, provided free of charge by the intact wetland. It matters for policy because if that wetland were destroyed (say, drained for development), the town would likely need to pay for artificial flood infrastructure — sea walls, levees, pumps — to replace a service nature was providing for free. This is exactly the kind of hidden economic value that environmental policy debates often center on: a wetland's "market value" as buildable land can look much higher than its ecological value, even though the ecosystem service it provides may be worth more in the long run.</div>
    </details>
  </div>

  <div class="recap">
    <span class="tag-label recap">Before You Move On</span>
    <ul>
      <li>Distinguish population, community, ecosystem, biome, and biosphere.</li>
      <li>Define ecosystem services and give at least three real examples.</li>
      <li>Explain why ecosystem services matter for environmental policy debates, even though they aren't directly bought or sold.</li>
    </ul>
  </div>

  <h2 id="s12"><span class="num">1.2</span>Terrestrial Biomes</h2>
  <p>Terrestrial biomes are determined primarily by two climate factors — average temperature and average precipitation — and once you know a region's climate, you can predict a great deal about its dominant vegetation and ecosystem structure.</p>

  <table class="formula-table">
    <thead><tr><th>Biome</th><th>Climate Pattern</th><th>Key Feature</th></tr></thead>
    <tbody>
      <tr><td>Tropical rainforest</td><td>Hot, high rainfall year-round</td><td>Highest biodiversity of any terrestrial biome; nutrient-poor soil (nutrients held in living biomass, not soil)</td></tr>
      <tr><td>Tropical seasonal forest/savanna</td><td>Hot, with a pronounced wet and dry season</td><td>Grassland with scattered trees; frequent fire-adapted vegetation</td></tr>
      <tr><td>Desert</td><td>Very low precipitation, extreme temperature swings</td><td>Sparse vegetation; low biodiversity; slow decomposition</td></tr>
      <tr><td>Temperate grassland</td><td>Moderate precipitation, insufficient to support forests</td><td>Deep, fertile soil; historically converted heavily to agriculture</td></tr>
      <tr><td>Temperate (deciduous) forest</td><td>Moderate temperature and precipitation, four distinct seasons</td><td>Trees that seasonally shed leaves</td></tr>
      <tr><td>Taiga / boreal forest</td><td>Cold, moderate precipitation</td><td>Coniferous (evergreen) trees; short growing season</td></tr>
      <tr><td>Tundra</td><td>Very cold, low precipitation</td><td>Permafrost (permanently frozen subsoil); no trees</td></tr>
    </tbody>
  </table>

  <div class="key-idea">
    <span class="tag-label idea">Key Idea — Tropical Rainforest Soil Is Deceptively Poor in Nutrients</span>
    <p>It's a genuinely common misconception that the lush, dense vegetation of a tropical rainforest implies rich soil. The opposite is true: because decomposition happens so fast in that hot, wet climate, nutrients are rapidly recycled back into living plants rather than accumulating in the soil — most of the ecosystem's nutrients are tied up in the living biomass itself, not stored in the ground. This is exactly why clearing a rainforest for farmland so often fails after just a few years: once the trees are gone, the thin, nutrient-poor soil underneath can't sustain intensive agriculture for long.</p>
  </div>

  <div class="trap">
    <span class="tag-label trap">Watch Out For This</span>
    <p>Don't assume biome type is determined by latitude alone. While latitude strongly influences temperature, precipitation is an equally important, independent factor — two regions at similar latitudes can be entirely different biomes (a desert and a tropical rainforest can both occur near the equator) depending on precipitation patterns, which are themselves shaped by factors like proximity to oceans, mountain ranges, and prevailing wind patterns.</p>
  </div>

  <div class="worked">
    <span class="tag-label example">Worked Example 2</span>
    <p><strong>Predicting a Biome from Climate Data.</strong> A region has an average annual temperature of 5°C and receives modest, consistent precipitation, with winters cold enough to support only coniferous, evergreen trees. Identify the likely biome.</p>
    <details class="solution"><summary>Show the reasoning</summary>
      <div class="sol-content">This description matches <strong>taiga (boreal forest)</strong> — a cold climate with moderate precipitation, dominated by coniferous trees adapted to a short growing season and harsh winters. The key distinguishing details are the cold average temperature (ruling out temperate or tropical biomes) combined with enough precipitation to support forest (ruling out tundra, which is too dry and cold even for coniferous trees).</div>
    </details>
  </div>

  <div class="recap">
    <span class="tag-label recap">Before You Move On</span>
    <ul>
      <li>Identify the two primary climate factors that determine terrestrial biome type.</li>
      <li>Match a described climate pattern to the correct terrestrial biome.</li>
      <li>Explain why tropical rainforest soil is nutrient-poor despite the biome's lush vegetation.</li>
    </ul>
  </div>

  <h2 id="s13"><span class="num">1.3</span>Aquatic Biomes</h2>
  <p>Aquatic biomes are organized around a different set of defining factors than terrestrial biomes — primarily salinity (fresh vs. salt water), depth, and the amount of light that penetrates the water.</p>

  <table class="formula-table">
    <thead><tr><th>Zone/Region</th><th>Description</th></tr></thead>
    <tbody>
      <tr><td>Photic zone</td><td>The upper layer of water light can penetrate, where photosynthesis can occur</td></tr>
      <tr><td>Aphotic zone</td><td>Deeper water with insufficient light for photosynthesis</td></tr>
      <tr><td>Littoral zone (lakes)</td><td>Shallow water near shore, supporting rooted aquatic plants</td></tr>
      <tr><td>Limnetic zone (lakes)</td><td>Open water, photic, away from shore</td></tr>
      <tr><td>Benthic zone</td><td>The bottom sediment layer of a body of water</td></tr>
      <tr><td>Estuary</td><td>Where a river meets the ocean, mixing fresh and salt water; extremely high productivity</td></tr>
    </tbody>
  </table>

  <div class="key-idea">
    <span class="tag-label idea">Key Idea — Estuaries and Wetlands Are Disproportionately Productive</span>
    <p>Estuaries — where freshwater rivers meet the salty ocean — are among the most biologically productive ecosystems on Earth, despite covering a comparatively small fraction of the planet's surface. This high productivity comes from a constant input of nutrients carried downstream by rivers, combined with shallow, sunlit water. Estuaries and coastal wetlands also serve as critical nursery habitats for an enormous number of marine species, which is exactly why their destruction (through development, pollution, or dredging) has consequences that ripple far beyond the immediate area, affecting fish populations across much broader ocean regions.</p>
  </div>

  <div class="trap">
    <span class="tag-label trap">Watch Out For This</span>
    <p>Lakes undergo seasonal turnover in temperate climates — a genuinely important process that's easy to memorize incorrectly. Water is DENSEST at 4°C, not at its freezing point. In spring and fall, surface water temperature passes through 4°C, becomes denser than the water below it, and sinks — mixing oxygen-rich surface water with nutrient-rich bottom water throughout the whole lake. This is why temperate lakes typically turn over TWICE a year (spring and fall), not just once — don't describe turnover as happening only in one season.</p>
  </div>

  <div class="worked">
    <span class="tag-label example">Worked Example 3</span>
    <p><strong>Explaining Lake Turnover.</strong> Explain why a deep temperate lake experiences a "turnover" event in both spring and fall, using the concept of water density.</p>
    <details class="solution"><summary>Show the reasoning</summary>
      <div class="sol-content">Water reaches its maximum density at 4°C. In summer, the lake is thermally stratified, with warm, less-dense water on top and cold, denser water below, separated by a thermocline that prevents mixing. As fall arrives and surface water cools toward 4°C, it becomes denser than the water below it and sinks, driving a full mixing of the lake — the fall turnover. Over winter, the coldest water (near 0°C, LESS dense than 4°C water) sits at the very top, just under any ice. In spring, as that surface ice melts and warms back toward 4°C, it again becomes denser than the layer below and sinks, driving a second full mixing event — the spring turnover. Both events redistribute oxygen and nutrients throughout the water column.</div>
    </details>
  </div>

  <div class="recap">
    <span class="tag-label recap">Before You Move On</span>
    <ul>
      <li>Distinguish the photic and aphotic zones, and the littoral, limnetic, and benthic zones of a lake.</li>
      <li>Explain why estuaries are disproportionately productive ecosystems.</li>
      <li>Explain lake turnover using the fact that water is densest at 4°C, and why it happens twice a year in temperate lakes.</li>
    </ul>
  </div>

  <h2 id="s14"><span class="num">1.4</span>The Hydrologic (Water) Cycle</h2>
  <p>The water cycle describes how water moves continuously between the atmosphere, land, and oceans — it's the first of this unit's biogeochemical cycles, and the one whose processes are probably already most familiar to you.</p>

  <table class="formula-table">
    <thead><tr><th>Process</th><th>Description</th></tr></thead>
    <tbody>
      <tr><td>Evaporation</td><td>Liquid water turning to water vapor, primarily from oceans and other surface water</td></tr>
      <tr><td>Transpiration</td><td>Water vapor released by plants; combined with evaporation, called evapotranspiration</td></tr>
      <tr><td>Condensation</td><td>Water vapor forming liquid droplets, creating clouds</td></tr>
      <tr><td>Precipitation</td><td>Water falling from the atmosphere as rain, snow, sleet, or hail</td></tr>
      <tr><td>Infiltration/Percolation</td><td>Water soaking into and moving down through soil into groundwater</td></tr>
      <tr><td>Runoff</td><td>Water flowing over land surface into streams, rivers, and eventually the ocean</td></tr>
    </tbody>
  </table>

  <div class="key-idea">
    <span class="tag-label idea">Key Idea — Land Use Changes the Balance Between Infiltration and Runoff</span>
    <p>Whether precipitation infiltrates into the ground or runs off across the surface depends heavily on land cover — a fact that connects the water cycle directly to Unit 5's land use content later in the course. A forest or healthy grassland, with roots and organic matter loosening the soil, allows substantial infiltration. A paved parking lot or compacted urban surface allows almost none, forcing nearly all precipitation into runoff instead. This shift toward more runoff and less infiltration is exactly why urbanization tends to increase flooding risk and reduce groundwater recharge in a region, even without any change in total precipitation.</p>
  </div>

  <div class="trap">
    <span class="tag-label trap">Watch Out For This</span>
    <p>Don't confuse an aquifer with a lake or an underground river. An aquifer is a saturated layer of permeable rock or sediment that holds groundwater within its pore spaces — it's not typically a large open cavern of water. A CONFINED aquifer is sandwiched between impermeable rock layers, protecting it from surface contamination but also making it slow to recharge; an UNCONFINED aquifer has no impermeable layer above it, recharging faster but also being more vulnerable to surface pollution infiltrating down into it.</p>
  </div>

  <div class="worked">
    <span class="tag-label example">Worked Example 4</span>
    <p><strong>Predicting a Land Use Effect on the Water Cycle.</strong> A forested watershed is clear-cut and converted to a paved parking lot. Predict the effect on infiltration, runoff, and local flooding risk, and explain why.</p>
    <details class="solution"><summary>Show the reasoning</summary>
      <div class="sol-content">Infiltration will <strong>decrease sharply</strong>, since pavement is essentially impermeable, unlike the loosened, root-filled forest soil it replaced. Runoff will <strong>increase sharply</strong> to compensate — water that would have soaked into the ground now flows across the paved surface instead. This combination means local flooding risk will <strong>increase</strong>, since a much larger share of any given rainfall now reaches streams and rivers quickly as surface runoff, rather than being absorbed and released slowly through the ground over time.</div>
    </details>
  </div>

  <div class="recap">
    <span class="tag-label recap">Before You Move On</span>
    <ul>
      <li>List and describe the major processes of the water cycle: evaporation, transpiration, condensation, precipitation, infiltration, and runoff.</li>
      <li>Explain how land use changes shift the balance between infiltration and runoff.</li>
      <li>Distinguish confined and unconfined aquifers in terms of contamination vulnerability and recharge rate.</li>
    </ul>
  </div>

  <h2 id="s15"><span class="num">1.5</span>The Carbon and Nitrogen Cycles</h2>
  <p>Carbon and nitrogen are both essential elements for life, and both cycle between living organisms and the nonliving environment — but the specific pathways each takes are genuinely different, and keeping them straight matters for this exam.</p>

  <div class="key-idea">
    <span class="tag-label idea">Key Idea — The Carbon Cycle Balances Photosynthesis Against Respiration and Combustion</span>
    <p>Carbon moves into living organisms primarily through photosynthesis (plants and other producers pulling CO<sub>2</sub> from the atmosphere and converting it into organic carbon compounds), and moves back out primarily through respiration (organisms breaking down those compounds, releasing CO<sub>2</sub>) and decomposition. Human activity adds a major additional pathway: burning fossil fuels releases carbon that had been stored underground for millions of years, adding it back into the active atmospheric cycle far faster than natural processes remove it — the central mechanism behind Unit 9's discussion of climate change.</p>
  </div>

  <div class="key-idea">
    <span class="tag-label idea">Key Idea — The Nitrogen Cycle Requires Bacteria at Almost Every Step</span>
    <p>Although the atmosphere is about 78% nitrogen gas (N<sub>2</sub>), most organisms cannot use nitrogen in that form directly — it has to be converted first, and specialized bacteria drive nearly every step of that conversion.</p>
  </div>

  <table class="formula-table">
    <thead><tr><th>Nitrogen Cycle Step</th><th>What Happens</th></tr></thead>
    <tbody>
      <tr><td>Nitrogen fixation</td><td>N<sub>2</sub> gas converted to usable ammonia/ammonium (NH<sub>3</sub>/NH<sub>4</sub><sup>+</sup>), mainly by nitrogen-fixing bacteria (e.g., Rhizobium in legume root nodules), also by lightning and industrial processes</td></tr>
      <tr><td>Nitrification</td><td>Ammonium converted to nitrite (NO<sub>2</sub><sup>−</sup>) then nitrate (NO<sub>3</sub><sup>−</sup>) by nitrifying bacteria</td></tr>
      <tr><td>Assimilation</td><td>Plants absorb nitrate/ammonium and incorporate nitrogen into organic molecules (proteins, DNA)</td></tr>
      <tr><td>Ammonification</td><td>Decomposers break down dead organisms and waste, releasing nitrogen back as ammonium</td></tr>
      <tr><td>Denitrification</td><td>Denitrifying bacteria convert nitrate back into N<sub>2</sub> gas, returning it to the atmosphere</td></tr>
    </tbody>
  </table>

  <div class="trap">
    <span class="tag-label trap">Watch Out For This</span>
    <p>Denitrification and nitrification are easy to mix up because they sound similar, but they move nitrogen in OPPOSITE directions. Nitrification converts ammonium INTO nitrate (usable forms, moving deeper into the biological cycle). Denitrification converts nitrate BACK INTO N<sub>2</sub> gas (returning nitrogen to the atmosphere, effectively removing it from biological availability). If a question describes bacteria releasing nitrogen gas back to the atmosphere, that's denitrification; if it describes ammonium being converted into nitrate, that's nitrification.</p>
  </div>

  <div class="worked">
    <span class="tag-label example">Worked Example 5</span>
    <p><strong>Tracing Nitrogen Fixation.</strong> Explain why legume crops (like soybeans or clover) are often planted specifically to improve soil fertility for future crops, using the nitrogen cycle.</p>
    <details class="solution"><summary>Show the reasoning</summary>
      <div class="sol-content">Legumes host nitrogen-fixing bacteria (like Rhizobium) in specialized root nodules. These bacteria convert atmospheric N<sub>2</sub> gas — which plants normally cannot use directly — into ammonia/ammonium, a usable form of nitrogen. As the legume plants grow and eventually decompose (or their roots remain in the soil), this newly fixed nitrogen becomes available in the soil for future crops to absorb through assimilation. This is exactly why crop rotation with legumes is a genuine, low-input way to naturally replenish soil nitrogen, reducing the need for synthetic nitrogen fertilizer.</div>
    </details>
  </div>

  <div class="recap">
    <span class="tag-label recap">Before You Move On</span>
    <ul>
      <li>Explain the carbon cycle's balance between photosynthesis, respiration, and fossil fuel combustion.</li>
      <li>Sequence the five major steps of the nitrogen cycle: fixation, nitrification, assimilation, ammonification, denitrification.</li>
      <li>Distinguish nitrification from denitrification, and explain why bacteria are essential to nearly every nitrogen cycle step.</li>
    </ul>
  </div>

  <h2 id="s16"><span class="num">1.6</span>The Phosphorus Cycle</h2>
  <p>The phosphorus cycle stands out from the other cycles covered in this unit for one genuinely distinctive reason, and understanding that distinction is the whole point of this section.</p>

  <div class="key-idea">
    <span class="tag-label idea">Key Idea — Phosphorus Has No Significant Atmospheric Phase</span>
    <p>Unlike carbon and nitrogen, phosphorus does not cycle through the atmosphere in any significant gaseous form — there's no phosphorus equivalent of CO<sub>2</sub> or N<sub>2</sub> moving through the air. Instead, phosphorus cycles primarily through rock, soil, and water: it's released slowly through the weathering of phosphate-containing rock, taken up by plants from soil or by aquatic producers from water, passed through food webs, and eventually returned to soil or sediment through decomposition and geological processes — a much slower cycle overall than carbon or nitrogen, precisely because it lacks a fast-moving atmospheric pathway.</p>
  </div>

  <div class="trap">
    <span class="tag-label trap">Watch Out For This</span>
    <p>Because phosphorus cycles so slowly and has no atmospheric reservoir to draw from, it's frequently the LIMITING NUTRIENT in freshwater aquatic ecosystems specifically — meaning the ecosystem's total productivity is capped by however much phosphorus is available, since organisms can't simply pull more from the air the way they effectively can with carbon and (via fixation) nitrogen. This is exactly why phosphorus runoff from fertilizer is such a significant water pollution concern (covered in more depth in Unit 8): adding phosphorus to a system where it was previously the limiting factor can trigger a dramatic, disproportionate increase in productivity — the mechanism behind eutrophication and algal blooms.</p>
  </div>

  <div class="worked">
    <span class="tag-label example">Worked Example 6</span>
    <p><strong>Explaining Why Phosphorus Runoff Causes Algal Blooms.</strong> A lake that previously had low algal growth experiences a sudden, dramatic algal bloom after nearby farms increase their use of phosphorus-based fertilizer. Explain this outcome using the concept of a limiting nutrient.</p>
    <details class="solution"><summary>Show the reasoning</summary>
      <div class="sol-content">If phosphorus was previously the <strong>limiting nutrient</strong> in this lake — the nutrient in shortest supply relative to what algae need to grow — then algal growth would have been capped by however little phosphorus was naturally available, regardless of how much of other nutrients (like carbon or nitrogen) were present. Once fertilizer runoff dramatically increases the phosphorus supply, that cap is suddenly lifted, allowing algae to grow explosively until some OTHER factor becomes limiting instead. This sudden, fertilizer-driven productivity surge is the core mechanism behind cultural eutrophication, a topic this course returns to in much greater depth in Unit 8.</div>
    </details>
  </div>

  <div class="recap">
    <span class="tag-label recap">Before You Move On</span>
    <ul>
      <li>Explain why the phosphorus cycle has no significant atmospheric component, unlike the carbon and nitrogen cycles.</li>
      <li>Explain why phosphorus is frequently the limiting nutrient in freshwater ecosystems.</li>
      <li>Connect excess phosphorus input to the mechanism behind eutrophication and algal blooms.</li>
    </ul>
  </div>

  <h2 id="s17"><span class="num">1.7</span>Energy Flow, Trophic Levels, and Productivity</h2>
  <p>This final section is where the unit's "energy flows one way" theme becomes fully concrete — describing exactly how much energy actually moves from one trophic level to the next, and why that number has such enormous consequences for how ecosystems are structured.</p>

  <table class="formula-table">
    <thead><tr><th>Trophic Level</th><th>Role</th></tr></thead>
    <tbody>
      <tr><td>Producers (autotrophs)</td><td>Capture energy directly from sunlight (or, rarely, chemical energy) via photosynthesis</td></tr>
      <tr><td>Primary consumers</td><td>Herbivores — eat producers directly</td></tr>
      <tr><td>Secondary consumers</td><td>Eat primary consumers (carnivores or omnivores)</td></tr>
      <tr><td>Tertiary consumers</td><td>Eat secondary consumers (often apex/top predators)</td></tr>
      <tr><td>Decomposers/Detritivores</td><td>Break down dead organic matter, returning nutrients to the system</td></tr>
    </tbody>
  </table>

  <div class="eq">
    <div class="main">NPP = GPP − R</div>
    <div class="sub">Net Primary Productivity = Gross Primary Productivity − Respiration (by producers)</div>
  </div>

  <div class="key-idea">
    <span class="tag-label idea">Key Idea — The 10% Rule</span>
    <p>On average, only about <strong>10%</strong> of the energy available at one trophic level is successfully transferred to the next trophic level up — the rest is lost, primarily as heat released during cellular respiration, along with energy used for movement, growth, and other life processes that never gets "passed on" up the food chain. This single number explains an enormous amount about ecosystem structure: it's why energy pyramids are always narrowest at the top (there simply isn't enough energy remaining to support many top predators), and why food chains rarely extend beyond four or five trophic levels — by the fifth level, there's typically too little energy left to sustain a viable population at all.</p>
  </div>

  <div class="trap">
    <span class="tag-label trap">Watch Out For This</span>
    <p>Gross Primary Productivity (GPP) and Net Primary Productivity (NPP) are frequently confused, and the exam tests the distinction directly. GPP is the TOTAL energy captured by producers through photosynthesis. NPP is what's LEFT OVER after producers use some of that energy for their own respiration (NPP = GPP − R) — NPP represents the energy actually available to be passed on to primary consumers and the rest of the food web. A producer with high GPP but also very high respiration could still have relatively low NPP, and NPP (not GPP) is the number that actually matters for how much energy supports the rest of the ecosystem.</p>
  </div>

  <div class="worked">
    <span class="tag-label example">Worked Example 7</span>
    <p><strong>Applying the 10% Rule.</strong> A field of grass has a net primary productivity of 10,000 kcal/m²/year. Using the 10% rule, estimate the energy available to secondary consumers (two trophic levels above the grass).</p>
    <details class="solution"><summary>Show the reasoning</summary>
      <div class="sol-content">Apply the 10% rule once per trophic level transition. From producers (grass) to primary consumers: 10,000 × 0.10 = <strong>1,000 kcal/m²/year</strong> available to primary consumers. From primary consumers to secondary consumers: 1,000 × 0.10 = <strong>100 kcal/m²/year</strong> available to secondary consumers. Notice how dramatically the available energy shrinks with each step — this is exactly why top predators are always relatively rare compared to the producers at the base of their food web; there simply isn't enough energy left by that point to support a large population.</div>
    </details>
  </div>

  <div class="recap">
    <span class="tag-label recap">Before You Move On</span>
    <ul>
      <li>Distinguish producers, primary/secondary/tertiary consumers, and decomposers.</li>
      <li>State and apply the formula NPP = GPP − R.</li>
      <li>Apply the 10% rule across multiple trophic levels, and explain why it limits food chain length and top predator abundance.</li>
    </ul>
  </div>

  <h2 id="s18"><span class="num">1.8</span>Ecological Pyramids: Energy, Biomass, and Numbers</h2>
  <p>The 10% rule is usually illustrated with an "energy pyramid," but energy is only one of three distinct ways ecologists visualize trophic structure — and a genuinely common exam trap involves assuming all three types of pyramid always behave the same way.</p>

  <table class="formula-table">
    <thead><tr><th>Pyramid Type</th><th>What It Measures</th><th>Can It Ever Be Inverted?</th></tr></thead>
    <tbody>
      <tr><td>Energy pyramid</td><td>Rate of energy flow through each trophic level</td><td>No — always upright, a direct consequence of the 10% rule</td></tr>
      <tr><td>Biomass pyramid</td><td>Total mass of living organisms present at each trophic level, at a given moment</td><td>Sometimes — particularly in aquatic ecosystems</td></tr>
      <tr><td>Numbers pyramid</td><td>Total count of individual organisms at each trophic level</td><td>Sometimes — particularly with a small number of very large producers</td></tr>
    </tbody>
  </table>

  <div class="key-idea">
    <span class="tag-label idea">Key Idea — Only the Energy Pyramid Is Guaranteed to Be Upright</span>
    <p>Because the 10% rule is a statement about the RATE of energy flow, the energy pyramid can never be inverted — each trophic level, by definition, can never receive more energy than the level below it provided. Biomass and numbers pyramids, however, measure a static SNAPSHOT of standing mass or population count at one moment in time, not a flow rate — and a snapshot can behave very differently from a flow. In many aquatic ecosystems, phytoplankton (the producers) have extremely high turnover — individual phytoplankton are consumed and replaced very quickly — so at any single moment, the standing biomass of phytoplankton present can actually be LOWER than the standing biomass of the zooplankton consuming them, even though the phytoplankton are still producing far more total energy over time. This produces an inverted biomass pyramid, despite the energy pyramid beneath it remaining perfectly normal and upright.</p>
  </div>

  <div class="trap">
    <span class="tag-label trap">Watch Out For This</span>
    <p>Don't assume that because an ecosystem has an inverted biomass or numbers pyramid, the 10% rule has somehow been violated — it hasn't. The energy pyramid underlying any ecosystem is always upright; biomass and numbers pyramids can look different specifically because they're measuring a standing snapshot of mass or count, not the underlying rate of energy flow. A classic numbers-pyramid example: a single large oak tree (one producer) can support thousands of individual insects (primary consumers) — more consumers in NUMBER than producers, even though the tree's total biomass and energy production still vastly exceed the insects'.</p>
  </div>

  <div class="worked">
    <span class="tag-label example">Worked Example 8</span>
    <p><strong>Explaining an Inverted Biomass Pyramid.</strong> A marine ecosystem shows a biomass pyramid where zooplankton (primary consumers) have greater standing biomass than the phytoplankton (producers) they feed on. Explain how this is possible without violating the 10% rule.</p>
    <details class="solution"><summary>Show the reasoning</summary>
      <div class="sol-content">This is possible because phytoplankton have an extremely rapid turnover rate — individual phytoplankton are consumed and reproduce very quickly, so the STANDING biomass present at any single snapshot in time can be small even while the total energy and biomass PRODUCED over a longer period is large. The zooplankton, with a slower turnover rate, accumulate and retain more standing biomass at any given moment. The underlying energy pyramid is still perfectly upright — the phytoplankton are still producing far more total energy than the zooplankton consume — it's specifically the standing biomass snapshot, not the energy flow rate, that appears inverted here.</div>
    </details>
  </div>

  <div class="recap">
    <span class="tag-label recap">Before You Move On</span>
    <ul>
      <li>Distinguish energy, biomass, and numbers pyramids by what each one measures.</li>
      <li>Explain why the energy pyramid can never be inverted, while biomass and numbers pyramids sometimes can be.</li>
      <li>Explain the phytoplankton/zooplankton turnover-rate mechanism behind an inverted aquatic biomass pyramid.</li>
    </ul>
  </div>

  <h2 id="practice">Unit 1 Practice Set</h2>
  <p>Work through every problem before checking the answer key.</p>


  <h3>Conceptual</h3>
  <div class="practice-item"><span class="qnum-badge">1</span><span>Distinguish a population, a community, and an ecosystem, using a coral reef as your example.</span></div>
  <div class="practice-item"><span class="qnum-badge">2</span><span>Explain why tropical rainforest soil is often nutrient-poor despite supporting extremely dense vegetation.</span></div>
  <div class="practice-item"><span class="qnum-badge">3</span><span>Explain why temperate lakes typically turn over twice per year rather than once.</span></div>
  <div class="practice-item"><span class="qnum-badge">4</span><span>Explain why phosphorus cycles more slowly than carbon or nitrogen.</span></div>
  <div class="practice-item"><span class="qnum-badge">5</span><span>Explain the 10% rule and its consequence for food chain length.</span></div>

  <h3>Application</h3>
  <div class="practice-item"><span class="qnum-badge">6</span><span>A region has hot temperatures year-round with a distinct wet and dry season, supporting grassland with scattered trees. Identify the biome.</span></div>
  <div class="practice-item"><span class="qnum-badge">7</span><span>A watershed is heavily paved for a new housing development. Predict the effect on infiltration and flooding risk.</span></div>
  <div class="practice-item"><span class="qnum-badge">8</span><span>Bacteria in a wetland convert nitrate (NO3−) back into N2 gas, releasing it to the atmosphere. Identify this process.</span></div>
  <div class="practice-item"><span class="qnum-badge">9</span><span>A field's producers have a GPP of 8,000 kcal/m²/year and use 3,000 kcal/m²/year for their own respiration. Find the NPP.</span></div>
  <div class="practice-item"><span class="qnum-badge">10</span><span>Using the NPP from Question 9, apply the 10% rule to estimate energy available to primary consumers.</span></div>
  <div class="practice-item"><span class="qnum-badge">11</span><span>A farmer plants clover (a legume) between growing seasons specifically to improve soil fertility. Explain the biological mechanism at work.</span></div>
  <div class="practice-item"><span class="qnum-badge">12</span><span>A lake's phosphorus levels rise sharply after nearby agricultural runoff. Predict and explain the likely effect on algal growth.</span></div>
  <div class="practice-item"><span class="qnum-badge">13</span><span>Identify the ecosystem service being described: a forest absorbs and stores atmospheric carbon dioxide.</span></div>

  <h3 style="margin-top:30px;">Answer Key</h3>
  <div class="answer-key">
    <details><summary>Question 1</summary><div class="a-content">A population would be all the individuals of one species on the reef (e.g., all the parrotfish). A community would be all the interacting species together (parrotfish, coral, algae, sharks, and more). An ecosystem would be that entire community plus the nonliving environment (water chemistry, sunlight, temperature, substrate).</div></details>
    <details><summary>Question 2</summary><div class="a-content">Because decomposition happens so rapidly in the hot, wet climate, nutrients are quickly recycled back into living plants rather than accumulating in the soil — most of the ecosystem's nutrients are stored in living biomass, not in the ground itself.</div></details>
    <details><summary>Question 3</summary><div class="a-content">Because water is densest at 4°C, not at its freezing point. As surface water cools toward 4°C in fall, and warms toward 4°C in spring, it becomes denser than the water below and sinks, driving a full mixing event at each of those two points during the year.</div></details>
    <details><summary>Question 4</summary><div class="a-content">Because phosphorus has no significant atmospheric (gaseous) phase — it cycles only through rock, soil, and water, which is a much slower pathway than carbon and nitrogen's fast atmospheric cycling.</div></details>
    <details><summary>Question 5</summary><div class="a-content">Only about 10% of energy at one trophic level transfers to the next, with the rest lost mainly as heat from respiration. This causes such a dramatic energy loss at each step that food chains rarely extend beyond four or five trophic levels, since there's too little energy left to sustain a population beyond that point.</div></details>
    <details><summary>Question 6</summary><div class="a-content">Tropical seasonal forest/savanna — the hot temperature with a distinct wet/dry season and grassland-with-scattered-trees structure is the defining combination for this biome.</div></details>
    <details><summary>Question 7</summary><div class="a-content">Infiltration would decrease sharply, since pavement is impermeable. Runoff would increase to compensate, and flooding risk would increase, since more precipitation now flows quickly across the surface rather than soaking into the ground.</div></details>
    <details><summary>Question 8</summary><div class="a-content">Denitrification — bacteria converting nitrate back into atmospheric nitrogen gas, removing it from biologically available forms.</div></details>
    <details><summary>Question 9</summary><div class="a-content">NPP = GPP − R = 8,000 − 3,000 = <strong>5,000 kcal/m²/year</strong>.</div></details>
    <details><summary>Question 10</summary><div class="a-content">5,000 × 0.10 = <strong>500 kcal/m²/year</strong> available to primary consumers.</div></details>
    <details><summary>Question 11</summary><div class="a-content">Clover hosts nitrogen-fixing bacteria in root nodules, converting atmospheric N2 (unusable by most plants) into ammonium, a usable form of nitrogen that enriches the soil for future crops through assimilation once the clover decomposes or its roots remain.</div></details>
    <details><summary>Question 12</summary><div class="a-content">Algal growth would likely increase sharply. If phosphorus was the limiting nutrient in this lake, the sudden increase in supply removes the cap on productivity, allowing algae to grow explosively — the mechanism behind eutrophication.</div></details>
    <details><summary>Question 13</summary><div class="a-content">Carbon sequestration/storage — a regulating ecosystem service, since it helps stabilize atmospheric CO2 concentrations at no direct cost to society.</div></details>
  </div>

  <div class="footer-nav">
    Next up: head to the <strong>Unit 1 QBank</strong> to drill these ideas, then move on to <strong>Unit 2 — The Living World: Biodiversity</strong>.
  </div>

</div>
